  "text": "The authors referred to this modified algorithm as the projected gradient iteration or the projected steeptest descent method. They have determined how large one can choose the successive γ n and have shown weak as well as strong convergence of the method (with and without acceleration) and gave numerical examples that clearly show the larger steps and faster convergence (when compared to (1.4)). Of course, there exist also other approaches for sparse recovery. Closely related to our approach are the methods presented in [CITATION_1] and [14] . However, the analysis in [14] is limited to finite dimensions and the strategy provided in [CITATION_2] is only suited for linear inverse problems. The principle there is to reformulate the minimization problem as a bounded constrained quadratic program, and then apply iterative project gradient iterations.",
